               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18280221-176-person1066">
                  JOSEPH 
                  WILSON
               <interp inst="t18280221-176-person1066" type="surname" value="WILSON"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18280221-176-person1066" type="given" value="JOSEPH"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18280221-176-person1066" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I know Mr. William Yool - he is a <rs id="t18280221-176-viclabel936" type="occupation">coal-merchant</rs>
                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t18280221-176-victim1065 t18280221-176-viclabel936"></join>. On the 16th of February, a little before two o'clock in the afternoon, I was going down in the craft on the river, and saw the Edward barge laying outside the dock of Brooks and Penny's wharf; I am their clerk. I saw the prisoner's head just over the barge, which was loaded with coals; he was taking coals out of the barge, into his boat; I came up to him, and he said, "If you will let me go, I will put them back," and he did throw two or three pieces back; I took hold of the chain of his boat, and held him till an officer came - I suppose there were nearly two bushels of coals in the boat- they appeared the same sort as those in the barge.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18280221-176-person1067">
                  ALEXANDER 
                  MITCHELL
               <interp inst="t18280221-176-person1067" type="surname" value="MITCHELL"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18280221-176-person1067" type="given" value="ALEXANDER"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18280221-176-person1067" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am an officer. I was sent for, to take the prisoner; Wilson was standing on the gunwale of the barge Edward, and had hold of the chain of the boat, in which there was about a bushel of small coals and two bushels of large coals; they appeared to me to be the same sort as those in the barge.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18280221-176-person1068">
                  CHRISTOPHER 
                  BEARPARK
               <interp inst="t18280221-176-person1068" type="surname" value="BEARPARK"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18280221-176-person1068" type="given" value="CHRISTOPHER"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18280221-176-person1068" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am wharf-clerk to Mr. William Yool. I went to the boat, and found the coals in it; they appeared to me to be part of the bulk of the barge Edward.</p>
               <p>COURT to 
               <persName id="t18280221-176-person1069">
                  ALEXANDER 
                  MITCHELL
               <interp inst="t18280221-176-person1069" type="surname" value="MITCHELL"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18280221-176-person1069" type="given" value="ALEXANDER"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18280221-176-person1069" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . Q. Did you hear the prisoner examined? A. Yes - this deposition was read over to him; this is Mr. Broderip's signature to it; there was no promise or threat made to the prisoner - (read).</p>
               <p>"I have been led into it, by keeping company with a man whom the officers know to be a noted thief."</p>
               <p>The prisoner put in a written defence, standing that the coals were only the sweepings of the barge. He received a good character.</p>
               <p>GUILTY. Aged 19.</p>
